Physical-device tests must cover:

- Multi-touch chords.
- Glissando.
- Audio unlock.
- Low-latency response.
- Rotation.
- Safe areas.
- Incoming interruption.
- Background and foreground.
- MP3 rendering.
- Native share sheet.
- WhatsApp appearing only when installed and compatible.
- Offline launch.
- Storage restoration.
- Installed-PWA storage behavior.

# 21. Deployment

The result must be deployable to any static HTTPS host.

Provide:

- npm run dev
- npm run build
- npm run preview
- npm run test
- npm run test:e2e
- npm run lint
- npm run typecheck

Set appropriate caching headers:

- HTML: no-cache or short-lived.
- Service worker: no-cache.
- Hashed JavaScript and CSS: immutable.
- Versioned piano samples: long-lived immutable.
- Manifest: short-lived or revalidated.

Create a deployment checklist.

Do not hardcode one hosting provider.

Include an example CI workflow that:

1. Installs dependencies from the lockfile.
2. Runs formatting checks.
3. Runs lint.
4. Runs type checking.
5. Runs unit tests.
6. Builds the application.
7. Runs suitable browser smoke tests.
8. Publishes the static dist directory.

# 22. Documentation

Create:

- README.md
- ARCHITECTURE.md
- THIRD_PARTY_NOTICES.md
- TAKE_FORMAT.md
- AUDIO_EXPORT.md
- PWA_AND_OFFLINE.md
- TESTING.md

README must explain:

- Local development.
- HTTPS requirements.
- Mobile-device testing.
- Installation on iPhone.
- Installation on Android.
- Desktop installation where supported.
- Offline sample download.
- Local storage behavior.
- JSON backup.
- MP3 sharing.
- Browser fallbacks.
- Known limitations.
- Deployment.

Document clearly:

- Takes are local to the current browser/application storage.
- Installing the PWA may create a separate storage context on some platforms.
- Users should export backups.
- Cross-device automatic synchronization is not part of version 1.
- Audio normally pauses when the app is backgrounded or the screen locks.
- The app does not use the microphone.

# 23. Performance targets

Meet these budgets on representative mid-range hardware:

- Perceived touch-to-sound latency of roughly 50 ms or less on physical devices.
- 60 fps keyboard interaction and score scrolling where hardware permits.
- Precached application shell of approximately 3 MB or less, excluding piano samples.
- Audio export renders faster than real time.
- A 2,000-note take remains scrollable and playable.
- No duplicate schedulers after rapid transport actions.
- No stuck notes after repeated rapid gestures.
- No audible metronome drift over a several-minute take.

# 24. Out of scope for version 1

Do not build these until every required feature is complete, but keep interfaces clean enough to add them later:

- Cloud accounts or synchronization.
- External MIDI-device input.
- MusicXML import or export.
- A full notation editor.
- Background audio playback.
- Microphone recording of any kind.
- AI composition or analysis features.
- Payments, subscriptions, or advertising.

# 25. Recommended implementation order

Implement in vertical slices:

1. Project setup: git initialization with a proper .gitignore, routing, theme, and strict TypeScript.
2. PWA manifest and service-worker shell.
3. Real-time sample-based piano engine.
4. Multi-touch keyboard.
5. Canonical take model.
6. Recording and transport state machine.
7. Grand-staff notation.
8. Metronome.
9. Playback synchronization.
10. IndexedDB persistence.
11. Take library.
12. JSON import, export, and backup.
13. Audible score scrubbing.
14. Offline piano-sample download.
15. Offline rendering.
16. MP3 Worker encoding.
17. Native share and download fallback.
18. Accessibility.
19. Device compatibility work.
20. Testing, documentation, and deployment.

# 26. Definition of done

The work is complete only when:

- The application is named PoKeyBoard everywhere.
- It runs from a normal HTTPS web URL.
- It is installable where supported.
- It opens as a standalone Home Screen web app on iPhone.
- It remains usable without installation.
- The application shell works offline.
- The downloaded piano sample pack works offline.
- The piano is sample-based.
- Multi-touch chords work.
- Glissando works.
- No keys remain stuck.
- The metronome remains synchronized.
- Notes appear on a grand staff.
- Performances are recorded as note events.
- Takes survive reloads and browser restarts under normal storage conditions.
- Takes can be opened, renamed, duplicated, and deleted.
- JSON import and export work.
- Full backup and restore work.
- Playback synchronizes score, playhead, audio, and keyboard.
- Paused score scrubbing auditions notes in both directions.
- Scrub timing follows scrolling speed.
- A take renders into a real MP3 file.
- The MP3 is playable.
- Direct file sharing works where supported.
- Download fallback works elsewhere.
- Export does not use microphone access.
- The application handles offline and interrupted states clearly.
- Core tests pass.
- Type checking passes.
- Linting passes.
- A production build succeeds.
- No core requirement is represented by a placeholder or TODO.

At the end, report:

- What was implemented.
- The final architecture.
- Commands that were run.
- Test, type-check, lint, and build results.
- Browsers and physical devices actually verified.
- PWA installation behavior verified.
- Offline behavior verified.
- Audio export formats verified.
- Any narrowly defined remaining issue.

Begin by inspecting the repository and then implement PoKeyBoard.